🧠 How to find versions from project code
🔹 1. Node.js / React (JavaScript projects)
✅ Check package.json
"engines": {
  "node": ">=18"
}

👉 This directly tells Node version

✅ Check .nvmrc
18

👉 Exact Node version

✅ Check lock files
package-lock.json
yarn.lock

👉 Not direct version, but confirms ecosystem

✅ If nothing found (fallback)

Look at dependencies:

"react": "^18.2.0"

👉 Safe choice:

Node 18 or Node 20
🚀 Docker image
FROM node:18
🔹 2. Python projects
✅ Check requirements.txt
flask==2.3.2

👉 Doesn’t show Python version directly ❗

✅ Check runtime.txt (VERY IMPORTANT)
python-3.10.6
✅ Check pyproject.toml
[tool.poetry.dependencies]
python = "^3.10"
✅ Check .python-version
3.11.2
🚀 Docker image
FROM python:3.10
🔹 3. Java projects
✅ Check pom.xml (Maven)
<properties>
  <java.version>17</java.version>
</properties>
✅ Check build.gradle
sourceCompatibility = '17'
🚀 Docker image
FROM openjdk:17
🔹 4. Go (Golang)
✅ Check go.mod
go 1.21
🚀 Docker image
FROM golang:1.21
🔹 5. .NET
✅ Check .csproj
<TargetFramework>net7.0</TargetFramework>
🚀 Docker image
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:7.0
🔹 6. Ruby
✅ Check Gemfile
ruby '3.2.0'
🚀 Docker image
FROM ruby:3.2
⚡ Universal DevOps Trick (Most Important)

If version is NOT mentioned anywhere:

👉 Safe approach:
Node → node:18 or node:20
Python → python:3.10
Java → openjdk:17

These are:
✔ Stable
✔ Widely supported
✔ Production safe

🔥 Pro-Level Trick (Real DevOps Engineers Use)

Run locally:

node -v
python --version
java -version

👉 Then match same version in Dockerfile

🧪 Folder Scan Strategy (SUPER IMPORTANT)

When you open any repo:

👉 Step 1:

ls

👉 Step 2: Look for:

package.json → Node
requirements.txt → Python
pom.xml → Java
go.mod → Go

👉 Step 3:
Open file → find version

🚀 Real Production Insight

Sometimes versions are defined in:

.dockerignore
.env
CI/CD (like Jenkinsfile, GitHub Actions)
🔥 Golden Rule

👉 Always match project version with Docker version

Mismatch = ❌ crashes, ❌ dependency issues

